03578nam a22006375i 9780814784358DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19981998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147843587 a10.18574/97808147843582doi  a(DE-B1597)546961  a(OCoLC)45844118  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDS558 .T66 1998 7aHIS0270702bisacsh04a959.70433731 aTomes, Robert R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aApocalypse Then :bAmerican Intellectuals and the Vietnam War, 1954-1975 /cRobert R. Tomes. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. A Long Time in the Comin' -- t2. Consensus and Commitment -- t3. The Search for Order -- t4. Skepticism and Dissent -- t5. The Collapse of the Liberal Consensus, 1968 -- t6. The Twilight of Liberalism, 1969-1975 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPrior to the Vietnam war, American intellectual life rested comfortably on shared assumptions and often common ideals. Intellectuals largely supported the social and economic reforms of the 1930s, the war against Hitler's Germany, and U.S. conduct during the Cold War. By the early 1960s, a liberal intellectual consensus existed. The war in Southeast Asia shattered this fragile coalition, which promptly dissolved into numerous camps, each of which questioned American institutions, values, and ideals. Robert R. Tomes sheds new light on the demise of Cold War liberalism and the development of the New Left, and the steady growth of a conservatism that used Vietnam, and anti-war sentiment, as a rallying point. Importantly, Tomes provides new evidence that neoconservatism retreated from internationalism due largely to Vietnam, only to regroup later with substantially diminished goals and expectations. Covering vast archival terrain, Apocalypse Then stands as the definitive account of the impact of the Vietnam war on American intellectual life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aIntellectualsxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xInfluence. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975zUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Military / Vietnam War.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814784358423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814784358.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK